Twitter-mediated political polarization in the 2020 election

Avik Bosshardt | Spring 2021 Capstone Artifact | COMP-440: Collective Intelligence

Analysis conducted with Charlotte Giang, Sarah Lipstone, and Gabriel Ramos

In 2020, Twitter acted as the frontline for an extremely polarized political war. As president Trump’s favorite social media platform, Twitter was front and center throughout the months-long presidential election campaign, but the cacophony of tweets reached a staggering peak in the days leading up to the election. Millions upon millions of election-related tweets poured into Twitter over the course of the campaign, and with so many distinct 280-character opinions, retweets, news articles, and more, you could be forgiven for thinking it impossible to extract a signal from the noise. But as it turns out, the tools of data science can extract quite a lot from our collective Twitter musings. We looked at a sample of some 24 million election tweets compiled by the IEEE to see what we could learn about ourselves, our politics, and what makes this election one for the history books.

The first sign that America’s political polarization had maybe gotten a bit out of hand came when we looked at the distribution of tweets by party. Tweets mentioning @POTUS. @GOP, Trump, Pence, or any republican campaign slogans dominated the Twitterverse from July through to mid-November, making up 56% of the 24 million tweets compared to 19% of the tweets which mention Democrat handles and slogans. Meanwhile 16% of tweets didn’t directly engage with either party, and 9% engaged with both parties.

The discourse on Twitter was clearly pretty lopsided, but ideally, we’d want to know not just who people were tweeting at, but what those people thought about them. This is where sentiment analysis comes in. Sentiment analysis is a text processing technique where emotional words are given a score based on the emotion they convey. For example, “hope” gets a positive score of 0.49, but “prison” gets a negative score of -0.59. By adding up the scores of the emotion words in each tweet, we can get a sense of how that tweeter was feeling. We can average these sentiments over weeks to figure out how people’s emotions changed over time. Below is a picture which really tells the whole story of this election: how people talked about each of the two major parties, week by week from July 1st to November 12th. Positive values indicate overall positive emotions in a given week, and negative values indicate overall negative emotions.

Even though Republicans were clearly the most mentioned party on Twitter, it seems they were also the most disliked. The sentiment directed at Republicans was consistently negative. This goes to show that (while tweets about Democrats were still quite positive), this was much more an election about removing Trump than electing Biden. It is interesting to see, though, that Republicans had mounting optimism before a slumping back into negative territory during week 45, the week of the election. We can zoom in on those final two weeks of the election to witness that drop in more detail. Election day was November 3, and the election was called on November 7.

Sentiments were fairly closely matched in the leadup to election day, but as soon as the election was called, a chasm opened between the two parties. We can take a look at some of the key words people were tweeting in those last two weeks. In the top image, Republican words, and in the bottom, Democrats.

In these word clouds, the intensity of competition is evident: victory is on both parties’ minds. And in the fringes, a troubling sign of what would come in the next few weeks: “enemies”, “lawsuit”, “fraud”. This is a pretty grim portrait of the election; it’s hard to deny the strength of emotion and vitriol which fueled the political discourse on social media.

But not every Twitter user was quite as engaged. 16% of the tweets in the dataset didn’t directly mention either party or candidate. The “neither” group is just as interesting as either party. Who are the people tweeting about neither party? The plot below shows the difference from the average distribution of tweets. For example, we know Republican tweets made up 55% of the dataset, but this plot shows that, of all the Portuguese tweets, only about 40% were about Republicans, a 15% drop. We can see that tweets in Spanish (the largest minority language in the US) are significantly more likely than average reference neither party. This trend holds true for the three largest non-English languages in the dataset.

What does it mean to tweet about neither party? Are these users less engaged, less polarized, or forced out of interaction by a language barrier? These questions are particularly important to ask of Spanish tweeters, of whom there are many in the US. While these patterns are interesting, we’re starting to run up against the limitations of the dataset. While we can get some ideas about what foreign language speakers are thinking (Portuguese speakers, for example, really like tweeting about Democrats, and really don't like tweeting about Republicans), the sentiment analysis was only conducted on English words. This means we can’t really get as deeply into the minds of foreign-language Twitter users as we can English speakers. However, the opinions of minority groups in the US, as well as the opinions of Twitter users from abroad, would be fascinating topics for future research.

There are also some limits to what sentiment analysis can do. When you simply assign a word a numeric value, you are missing out on the context in which that word was used, which can often dramatically alter what a word means. Sarcasm, for example, effectively negates the sentiment of whatever you’re saying, but we’d have no way of detecting that.

And of course, we should acknowledge that all data is biased. There are a lot of people on Twitter, of all political ideologies, but we can't assume that Twitter is a representative sample of people who had opinions on the election. Recent news stories have reported that, especially in the days and weeks following the election, conservatives have been fleeing the most popular social media sites for new ones due to Twitter's and others efforts to quell the spread of misinformation on the platform. This is an excellect example of how the people who use Twitter can be quite different from the population as a whole.

Despite limitations, what we uncovered closely tracked with our intuition and our lived experiences this election season. It paints a grim picture of an America divided, and we have a long road ahead if we ever hope to heal.
